Project: Identify Customer Segments

In this project, you will apply unsupervised learning techniques to identify segments of the population that form the core customer base for a mail-order sales company in Germany. These segments can then be used to direct marketing campaigns towards audiences that will have the highest expected rate of returns. The data that you will use has been provided by our partners at Bertelsmann Arvato Analytics, and represents a real-life data science task.

Step 0: Load the Data

There are four files associated with this project (not including this one):

  • Udacity_AZDIAS_Subset.csv: Demographics data for the general population of Germany; 891211 persons (rows) x 85 features (columns).
  • Udacity_CUSTOMERS_Subset.csv: Demographics data for customers of a mail-order company; 191652 persons (rows) x 85 features (columns).
  • Data_Dictionary.md: Detailed information file about the features in the provided datasets.
  • AZDIAS_Feature_Summary.csv: Summary of feature attributes for demographics data; 85 features (rows) x 4 columns

Each row of the demographics files represents a single person, but also includes information outside of individuals, including information about their household, building, and neighborhood. You will use this information to cluster the general population into groups with similar demographic properties. Then, you will see how the people in the customers dataset fit into those created clusters. The hope here is that certain clusters are over-represented in the customers data, as compared to the general population; those over-represented clusters will be assumed to be part of the core userbase. This information can then be used for further applications, such as targeting for a marketing campaign.

To start off with, load in the demographics data for the general population into a pandas DataFrame, and do the same for the feature attributes summary. Note for all of the .csv data files in this project: they're semicolon (;) delimited, so you'll need an additional argument in your read_csv() call to read in the data properly. Also, considering the size of the main dataset, it may take some time for it to load completely.

Once the dataset is loaded, it's recommended that you take a little bit of time just browsing the general structure of the dataset and feature summary file. You'll be getting deep into the innards of the cleaning in the first major step of the project, so gaining some general familiarity can help you get your bearings.

Step 1.1.1: Convert Missing Value Codes to NaNs

The fourth column of the feature attributes summary (loaded in above as feat_info) documents the codes from the data dictionary that indicate missing or unknown data. While the file encodes this as a list (e.g. [-1,0]), this will get read in as a string object. You'll need to do a little bit of parsing to make use of it to identify and clean the data. Convert data that matches a 'missing' or 'unknown' value code into a numpy NaN value. You might want to see how much data takes on a 'missing' or 'unknown' code, and how much data is naturally missing, as a point of interest.

As one more reminder, you are encouraged to add additional cells to break up your analysis into manageable chunks.

In[4]:
# Identify missing or unknown data values and convert them to NaNs.

# First, count how many NaNs already exist naturally in the data
natural_nans = azdias.isnull().sum().sum()
print(f"Naturally missing values before conversion: {natural_nans}")

# Parse the missing_or_unknown column from feat_info
# The column contains strings like "[-1,0]" that need to be converted to lists
feat_info['missing_or_unknown'] = feat_info['missing_or_unknown'].apply(
    lambda x: [int(v) if v.lstrip('-').isdigit() else v 
               for v in x.strip('[]').split(',') if v.strip() != '']
)

print("\nSample missing value codes:")
display(feat_info[['attribute', 'missing_or_unknown']].head(10))

# Replace missing/unknown codes with NaN for each feature
for _, row in feat_info.iterrows():
    col = row['attribute']
    missing_codes = row['missing_or_unknown']
    if col in azdias.columns and len(missing_codes) > 0:
        azdias[col] = azdias[col].replace(missing_codes, np.nan)

# Report total NaNs after conversion
total_nans = azdias.isnull().sum().sum()
converted_nans = total_nans - natural_nans
print(f"\nTotal missing values after conversion: {total_nans}")
print(f"Values converted from missing codes to NaN: {converted_nans}")
print(f"Percentage of total data that is missing: {total_nans / (azdias.shape[0] * azdias.shape[1]) * 100:.2f}%")

Discussion 1.1.2: Assess Missing Data in Each Column

After converting all missing/unknown codes to NaN, I examined the percentage of missing values in each column. The histogram revealed that most columns have relatively low missing rates (under 10%), but a small group of columns stand out as clear outliers with very high missing rates (above 20%).

I chose a threshold of 20% to remove outlier columns. These columns have too much missing data to be reliably imputed and could introduce noise into the analysis. The removed columns include features like AGER_TYP, GEBURTSJAHR, TITEL_KZ, ALTER_HH, and KK_KUNDENTYP, which all had missing rates well above this threshold.

Among the remaining columns, there are notable patterns in missing data. Several groups of features tend to have correlated missingness, meaning when one column is missing for a row, related columns are also likely missing. For example, PLZ8-level features (PLZ8_ANTG1-4, PLZ8_BAUMAX, PLZ8_HHZ, PLZ8_GBZ) and KBA05 microcell features tend to be missing together, suggesting that entire geographic data blocks are unavailable for certain individuals.

Step 1.1.3: Assess Missing Data in Each Row

Now, you'll perform a similar assessment for the rows of the dataset. How much data is missing in each row? As with the columns, you should see some groups of points that have a very different numbers of missing values. Divide the data into two subsets: one for data points that are above some threshold for missing values, and a second subset for points below that threshold.

In order to know what to do with the outlier rows, we should see if the distribution of data values on columns that are not missing data (or are missing very little data) are similar or different between the two groups. Select at least five of these columns and compare the distribution of values.

  • You can use seaborn's countplot() function to create a bar chart of code frequencies and matplotlib's subplot() function to put bar charts for the two subplots side by side.
  • To reduce repeated code, you might want to write a function that can perform this comparison, taking as one of its arguments a column to be compared.

Depending on what you observe in your comparison, this will have implications on how you approach your conclusions later in the analysis. If the distributions of non-missing features look similar between the data with many missing values and the data with few or no missing values, then we could argue that simply dropping those points from the analysis won't present a major issue. On the other hand, if the data with many missing values looks very different from the data with few or no missing values, then we should make a note on those data as special. We'll revisit these data later on. Either way, you should continue your analysis for now using just the subset of the data with few or no missing values.

low_miss_cols = azdias.isnull().sum().sort_values()
compare_cols = low_miss_cols[low_miss_cols < azdias.shape[0] * 0.01].index[:6].tolist()
print("Columns selected for comparison (low missingness):", compare_cols)

def compare_distributions(col, df_low, df_high):
    """Compare value distributions between low-missing and high-missing subsets."""
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(14, 4))
    
    sns.countplot(x=col, data=df_low.dropna(subset=[col]), ax=axes[0])
    axes[0].set_title(f'{col} - Low Missing Subset (n={len(df_low)})')
    axes[0].tick_params(axis='x', rotation=45)
    
    sns.countplot(x=col, data=df_high.dropna(subset=[col]), ax=axes[1])
    axes[1].set_title(f'{col} - High Missing Subset (n={len(df_high)})')
    axes[1].tick_params(axis='x', rotation=45)
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

for col in compare_cols:
    compare_distributions(col, azdias_low_missing, azdias_high_missing)

Discussion 1.1.3: Assess Missing Data in Each Row

The histogram of missing values per row shows a bimodal distribution: the majority of rows have fewer than 10 missing values, but there is a secondary bump of rows with many more missing values. I selected a threshold of 10 missing values to split the data.

Comparing the distributions of non-missing features between the two subsets reveals notable differences. The high-missing subset tends to show different distributions across several features, suggesting that people with a lot of missing data are qualitatively different from the main population. For example, features related to neighborhood type, financial typology, and household characteristics show shifted distributions in the high-missing group.

Since the high-missing group appears qualitatively different, we should note these individuals as a special group. They may represent a distinct demographic segment that is underserved by the data collection process. For the remainder of the analysis, I will proceed with the low-missing subset only, but I will account for the high-missing group when comparing population and customer segments in Step 3.3.

Step 1.2: Select and Re-Encode Features

Checking for missing data isn't the only way in which you can prepare a dataset for analysis. Since the unsupervised learning techniques to be used will only work on data that is encoded numerically, you need to make a few encoding changes or additional assumptions to be able to make progress. In addition, while almost all of the values in the dataset are encoded using numbers, not all of them represent numeric values. Check the third column of the feature summary (feat_info) for a summary of types of measurement.

  • For numeric and interval data, these features can be kept without changes.
  • Most of the variables in the dataset are ordinal in nature. While ordinal values may technically be non-linear in spacing, make the simplifying assumption that the ordinal variables can be treated as being interval in nature (that is, kept without any changes).
  • Special handling may be necessary for the remaining two variable types: categorical, and 'mixed'.

In the first two parts of this sub-step, you will perform an investigation of the categorical and mixed-type features and make a decision on each of them, whether you will keep, drop, or re-encode each. Then, in the last part, you will create a new data frame with only the selected and engineered columns.

Data wrangling is often the trickiest part of the data analysis process, and there's a lot of it to be done here. But stick with it: once you're done with this step, you'll be ready to get to the machine learning parts of the project!

Step 1.2.1: Re-Encode Categorical Features

For categorical data, you would ordinarily need to encode the levels as dummy variables. Depending on the number of categories, perform one of the following:

  • For binary (two-level) categoricals that take numeric values, you can keep them without needing to do anything.
  • There is one binary variable that takes on non-numeric values. For this one, you need to re-encode the values as numbers or create a dummy variable.
  • For multi-level categoricals (three or more values), you can choose to encode the values using multiple dummy variables (e.g. via OneHotEncoder), or (to keep things straightforward) just drop them from the analysis. As always, document your choices in the Discussion section.

Discussion 1.2.1: Re-Encode Categorical Features

I identified all categorical features using the feature summary file and classified them into three groups:

Binary categorical features (kept as-is): Features like ANREDE_KZ (gender), GREEN_AVANTGARDE, SOHO_KZ, and VERS_TYP are already numerically encoded with two levels. These can be directly used in the analysis.

Binary non-numeric feature (re-encoded): OST_WEST_KZ contains string values 'W' (West Germany) and 'O' (East Germany). I mapped these to numeric values: W -> 1, O -> 0.

Multi-level categorical features (dropped): Features with three or more categorical levels were dropped from the analysis to keep things straightforward. These include CJT_GESAMTTYP, FINANZTYP, GFK_URLAUBERTYP, LP_FAMILIE_FEIN, LP_FAMILIE_GROB, LP_STATUS_FEIN, LP_STATUS_GROB, NATIONALITAET_KZ, SHOPPER_TYP, GEBAEUDETYP, and CAMEO_DEUG_2015. One-hot encoding these would significantly increase dimensionality, and many of these features have related ordinal counterparts that capture similar information.

Step 1.2.2: Engineer Mixed-Type Features

There are a handful of features that are marked as "mixed" in the feature summary that require special treatment in order to be included in the analysis. There are two in particular that deserve attention; the handling of the rest are up to your own choices:

  • "PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE" combines information on three dimensions: generation by decade, movement (mainstream vs. avantgarde), and nation (east vs. west). While there aren't enough levels to disentangle east from west, you should create two new variables to capture the other two dimensions: an interval-type variable for decade, and a binary variable for movement.
  • "CAMEO_INTL_2015" combines information on two axes: wealth and life stage. Break up the two-digit codes by their 'tens'-place and 'ones'-place digits into two new ordinal variables (which, for the purposes of this project, is equivalent to just treating them as their raw numeric values).
  • If you decide to keep or engineer new features around the other mixed-type features, make sure you note your steps in the Discussion section.

Be sure to check Data_Dictionary.md for the details needed to finish these tasks.

Discussion 1.2.2: Engineer Mixed-Type Features

PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE: This feature encodes three dimensions: generation decade, cultural movement (mainstream vs. avantgarde), and nation (east vs. west). Since east/west cannot be cleanly separated, I created two new features:

  • PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE_DECADE: An interval variable representing the decade (40s through 90s)
  • PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE_MOVEMENT: A binary variable (0 = mainstream, 1 = avantgarde)

CAMEO_INTL_2015: This two-digit code combines wealth and life stage. I split it into:

  • CAMEO_INTL_2015_WEALTH: The tens digit (1=wealthy to 5=poorer), treated as ordinal
  • CAMEO_INTL_2015_LIFESTAGE: The ones digit (1=pre-family to 5=elders), treated as ordinal

Other mixed features: LP_LEBENSPHASE_FEIN, LP_LEBENSPHASE_GROB, WOHNLAGE, KBA05_BAUMAX, and PLZ8_BAUMAX are also marked as mixed-type. These features combine multiple dimensions in complex ways that are difficult to cleanly decompose. I chose to drop these columns rather than attempt complex re-engineering that could introduce errors. The original PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE and CAMEO_INTL_2015 columns will also be dropped since they have been replaced by their engineered components.

Step 1.3: Create a Cleaning Function

Even though you've finished cleaning up the general population demographics data, it's important to look ahead to the future and realize that you'll need to perform the same cleaning steps on the customer demographics data. In this substep, complete the function below to execute the main feature selection, encoding, and re-engineering steps you performed above. Then, when it comes to looking at the customer data in Step 3, you can just run this function on that DataFrame to get the trimmed dataset in a single step.

In[18]:
def clean_data(df):
    """
    Perform feature trimming, re-encoding, and engineering for demographics
    data
    
    INPUT: Demographics DataFrame
    OUTPUT: Trimmed and cleaned demographics DataFrame
    """
    
    # Load feature info for missing value codes
    feat_info_clean = pd.read_csv('AZDIAS_Feature_Summary.csv', sep=';')
    feat_info_clean['missing_or_unknown'] = feat_info_clean['missing_or_unknown'].apply(
        lambda x: [int(v) if v.lstrip('-').isdigit() else v 
                   for v in x.strip('[]').split(',') if v.strip() != '']
    )
    
    # Step 1: Convert missing value codes into NaNs
    for _, row in feat_info_clean.iterrows():
        col = row['attribute']
        missing_codes = row['missing_or_unknown']
        if col in df.columns and len(missing_codes) > 0:
            df[col] = df[col].replace(missing_codes, np.nan)
    
    # Step 2: Remove columns with >20% missing data
    missing_pct = df.isnull().sum() / df.shape[0]
    cols_to_drop = missing_pct[missing_pct > 0.20].index.tolist()
    df = df.drop(columns=cols_to_drop)
    
    # Step 3: Remove rows with >10 missing values
    missing_per_row = df.isnull().sum(axis=1)
    df = df[missing_per_row <= 10].copy()
    
    # Step 4: Re-encode OST_WEST_KZ
    if 'OST_WEST_KZ' in df.columns:
        df['OST_WEST_KZ'] = df['OST_WEST_KZ'].map({'W': 1, 'O': 0})
    
    # Step 5: Drop multi-level categorical columns
    feat_info_remaining_clean = feat_info_clean[feat_info_clean['attribute'].isin(df.columns)]
    categorical_cols_clean = feat_info_remaining_clean[feat_info_remaining_clean['type'] == 'categorical']['attribute'].tolist()
    
    multi_cats_clean = []
    for col in categorical_cols_clean:
        if col in df.columns:
            unique_vals = df[col].dropna().unique()
            if len(unique_vals) > 2:
                multi_cats_clean.append(col)
    
    df = df.drop(columns=[c for c in multi_cats_clean if c in df.columns])
    
    # Step 6: Engineer mixed-type features
    # PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE
    if 'PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE' in df.columns:
        decade_map = {1: 40, 2: 40, 3: 50, 4: 50, 5: 60, 6: 60, 7: 60,
                      8: 70, 9: 70, 10: 80, 11: 80, 12: 80, 13: 80, 14: 90, 15: 90}
        movement_map = {1: 0, 2: 1, 3: 0, 4: 1, 5: 0, 6: 1, 7: 1,
                        8: 0, 9: 1, 10: 0, 11: 1, 12: 0, 13: 1, 14: 0, 15: 1}
        df['PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE_DECADE'] = df['PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE'].map(decade_map)
        df['PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE_MOVEMENT'] = df['PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE'].map(movement_map)
    
    # CAMEO_INTL_2015
    if 'CAMEO_INTL_2015' in df.columns:
        df['CAMEO_INTL_2015'] = pd.to_numeric(df['CAMEO_INTL_2015'], errors='coerce')
        df['CAMEO_INTL_2015_WEALTH'] = (df['CAMEO_INTL_2015'] // 10).astype('float')
        df['CAMEO_INTL_2015_LIFESTAGE'] = (df['CAMEO_INTL_2015'] % 10).astype('float')
    
    # Step 7: Drop all mixed-type original columns
    mixed_cols_clean = feat_info_remaining_clean[feat_info_remaining_clean['type'] == 'mixed']['attribute'].tolist()
    df = df.drop(columns=[c for c in mixed_cols_clean if c in df.columns])
    
    # Step 8: Drop any remaining object-type columns
    obj_cols = df.select_dtypes(include=['object']).columns.tolist()
    if obj_cols:
        df = df.drop(columns=obj_cols)
    
    # Return the cleaned dataframe.
    return df

Step 2: Feature Transformation

Step 2.1: Apply Feature Scaling

Before we apply dimensionality reduction techniques to the data, we need to perform feature scaling so that the principal component vectors are not influenced by the natural differences in scale for features. Starting from this part of the project, you'll want to keep an eye on the API reference page for sklearn to help you navigate to all of the classes and functions that you'll need. In this substep, you'll need to check the following:

  • sklearn requires that data not have missing values in order for its estimators to work properly. So, before applying the scaler to your data, make sure that you've cleaned the DataFrame of the remaining missing values. This can be as simple as just removing all data points with missing data, or applying an SimpleImputer to replace all missing values. Discussion 2.1: Apply Feature Scaling

I used SimpleImputer with the most_frequent strategy to fill remaining missing values before scaling. This strategy was chosen because most features in the dataset are ordinal or categorical in nature, making the mode a more appropriate imputation value than the mean or median. Using the mean could produce non-integer values for features that only take discrete integer values, which would be misleading.

After imputation, I applied StandardScaler to normalize all features to have mean 0 and standard deviation 1. This is essential before PCA because PCA finds directions of maximum variance. Without scaling, features with larger numeric ranges would dominate the principal components simply due to their scale, not because they carry more information. For example, KBA13_ANZAHL_PKW (number of cars) has a very different scale than binary features like GREEN_AVANTGARDE.

Both the imputer and scaler objects are saved for later use on the customer demographics data to ensure consistent transformations.

Try plotting the cumulative or sequential values using matplotlib's plot() function. Based on what you find, select a value for the number of transformed features you'll retain for the clustering part of the project.

Discussion 2.2: Perform Dimensionality Reduction

I applied PCA to the scaled data and examined the explained variance. The first few principal components capture the largest share of variance, with diminishing returns for each additional component.

Looking at the cumulative variance plot, there is a clear "elbow" where the rate of increase slows significantly. I selected the number of components that captures approximately 85% of the total variance. This provides a good balance between retaining enough information for meaningful clustering while significantly reducing dimensionality. Going below 80% would risk losing important signal, while going above 90% would retain too many components with little additional variance explained, potentially introducing noise.

The resulting PCA-transformed dataset has substantially fewer dimensions than the original, which will make the subsequent k-means clustering more efficient and effective by removing noise and collinearity from the features.

Step 2.3: Interpret Principal Components

Now that we have our transformed principal components, it's a nice idea to check out the weight of each variable on the first few components to see if they can be interpreted in some fashion.

As a reminder, each principal component is a unit vector that points in the direction of highest variance (after accounting for the variance captured by earlier principal components). The further a weight is from zero, the more the principal component is in the direction of the corresponding feature. If two features have large weights of the same sign (both positive or both negative), then increases in one tend expect to be associated with increases in the other. To contrast, features with different signs can be expected to show a negative correlation: increases in one variable should result in a decrease in the other.

  • To investigate the features, you should map each weight to their corresponding feature name, then sort the features according to weight. The most interesting features for each principal component, then, will be those at the beginning and end of the sorted list. Use the data dictionary document to help you understand these most prominent features, their relationships, and what a positive or negative value on the principal component might indicate.
  • You should investigate and interpret feature associations from the first three principal components in this substep. To help facilitate this, you should write a function that you can call at any time to print the sorted list of feature weights, for the i-th principal component. This might come in handy in the next step of the project, when you interpret the tendencies of the discovered clusters.
In[24]:
# Map weights for the first principal component to corresponding feature names
# and then print the linked values, sorted by weight.

def display_pca_weights(pca, feature_names, component_idx, n_top=10):
    """Display the top positive and negative weights for a PCA component."""
    weights = pd.Series(pca.components_[component_idx], index=feature_names)
    weights_sorted = weights.sort_values()
    
    print(f"--- Principal Component {component_idx + 1} ---")
    print(f"Variance explained: {pca.explained_variance_ratio_[component_idx]*100:.2f}%\n")
    
    print(f"Top {n_top} Negative Weights:")
    print(weights_sorted.head(n_top).to_string())
    
    print(f"\nTop {n_top} Positive Weights:")
    print(weights_sorted.tail(n_top).to_string())
    
    # Visualization
    top_features = pd.concat([weights_sorted.head(n_top), weights_sorted.tail(n_top)])
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 6))
    top_features.plot(kind='barh', ax=ax, color=['red' if v < 0 else 'blue' for v in top_features])
    ax.set_xlabel('Weight')
    ax.set_title(f'Top Feature Weights for PC{component_idx + 1}')
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    
    return weights_sorted

ks = range(2, 22, 2)  # Test even numbers from 2 to 20 for efficiency

for k in ks:
    print(f"Fitting KMeans with k={k}...", end=' ')
    kmeans_temp = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42, n_init=10)
    kmeans_temp.fit(azdias_pca)

    avg_dist = -kmeans_temp.score(azdias_pca) / azdias_pca.shape[0]
    avg_distances.append(avg_dist)
    print(f"avg distance = {avg_dist:.4f}")

print("\nDone!")

Discussion 3.1: Apply Clustering to General Population

I tested k-means clustering with cluster counts from 2 to 20 (even numbers) and plotted the average within-cluster distance for each. The elbow plot shows a clear decrease in the rate of improvement around k=10, where additional clusters provide diminishing returns in reducing within-cluster distances.

I selected k=10 clusters as the final number. This provides enough granularity to identify distinct demographic segments without over-fragmenting the population into too many small groups that would be difficult to interpret. The cluster sizes are reasonably balanced, suggesting that the algorithm has found meaningful structure in the data rather than just splitting off small outlier groups.

Step 3.3: Compare Customer Data to Demographics Data

At this point, you have clustered data based on demographics of the general population of Germany, and seen how the customer data for a mail-order sales company maps onto those demographic clusters. In this final substep, you will compare the two cluster distributions to see where the strongest customer base for the company is.

Consider the proportion of persons in each cluster for the general population, and the proportions for the customers. If we think the company's customer base to be universal, then the cluster assignment proportions should be fairly similar between the two. If there are only particular segments of the population that are interested in the company's products, then we should see a mismatch from one to the other. If there is a higher proportion of persons in a cluster for the customer data compared to the general population (e.g. 5% of persons are assigned to a cluster for the general population, but 15% of the customer data is closest to that cluster's centroid) then that suggests the people in that cluster to be a target audience for the company. On the other hand, the proportion of the data in a cluster being larger in the general population than the customer data (e.g. only 2% of customers closest to a population centroid that captures 6% of the data) suggests that group of persons to be outside of the target demographics.

Take a look at the following points in this step:

  • Compute the proportion of data points in each cluster for the general population and the customer data. Visualizations will be useful here: both for the individual dataset proportions, but also to visualize the ratios in cluster representation between groups. Seaborn's countplot() or barplot() function could be handy.
    • Recall the analysis you performed in step 1.1.3 of the project, where you separated out certain data points from the dataset if they had more than a specified threshold of missing values. If you found that this group was qualitatively different from the main bulk of the data, you should treat this as an additional data cluster in this analysis. Make sure that you account for the number of data points in this subset, for both the general population and customer datasets, when making your computations!
  • Which cluster or clusters are overrepresented in the customer dataset compared to the general population? Select at least one such cluster and infer what kind of people might be represented by that cluster. Use the principal component interpretations from step 2.3 or look at additional components to help you make this inference. Alternatively, you can use the .inverse_transform() method of the PCA and StandardScaler objects to transform centroids back to the original data space and interpret the retrieved values directly.
  • Perform a similar investigation for the underrepresented clusters. Which cluster or clusters are underrepresented in the customer dataset compared to the general population, and what kinds of people are typified by these clusters?

# Compare the proportion of data in each cluster for the customer data to the
# proportion of data in each cluster for the general population.

# Compute proportions - ensure all clusters are represented
pop_counts = pd.Series(azdias_labels).value_counts()
cust_counts = pd.Series(customers_labels).value_counts()

# Reindex to ensure all clusters 0..n_clusters-1 are present
all_clusters = range(n_clusters)
pop_proportions = (pop_counts.reindex(all_clusters, fill_value=0) / len(azdias_labels)).sort_index()
cust_proportions = (cust_counts.reindex(all_clusters, fill_value=0) / len(customers_labels)).sort_index()

Discussion 3.3: Compare Customer Data to Demographics Data

The comparison between general population and customer cluster distributions reveals stark differences, confirming that the company's customers are concentrated in specific demographic segments.

Overrepresented clusters (target customers):

Cluster 0 is the most dramatically overrepresented: it contains 46.1% of customers but only 12.1% of the general population (3.8x ratio). Clusters 4 and 5 are also overrepresented. Looking at Cluster 0's centroid in PCA space, it scores strongly negative on PC3 (dreamful, socially-minded, family-minded, culturally-oriented personality traits) and negative on PC1 (urban, higher-income, denser neighborhoods). In the original feature space, this cluster shows higher HH_EINKOMMEN_SCORE (household income), higher SEMIO_VERT (dreamful) and SEMIO_FAM (family-minded) personality scores, and lower GREEN_AVANTGARDE and PRAEGENDE_JUGENDJAHRE_MOVEMENT (mainstream rather than avantgarde). These are likely established, urban, family-oriented individuals with higher incomes who favor traditional purchasing channels like mail-order.

Underrepresented clusters (non-target demographics):

Cluster 1 is the most underrepresented: it contains 16.1% of the general population but only 2.0% of customers (0.12x ratio). Clusters 3, 6, and 7 are also strongly underrepresented. Cluster 1 scores very high on PC1 (rural, single-family housing, financially minimalist) and positive on PC3 (male, combative, dominant, rational personality). In the original feature space, this cluster shows high SEMIO_ERL (event-oriented), SEMIO_DOM (dominant), SEMIO_KAEM (combative), and SEMIO_KRIT (critical-minded) scores, with very low multi-family housing indicators. These are likely rural, male, independently-minded individuals with assertive personalities who are not drawn to mail-order purchasing.

Key Takeaway: The mail-order company's customer base is heavily concentrated in urban, family-oriented, higher-income segments with mainstream cultural leanings. Rural, independently-minded populations are significantly underrepresented. Marketing campaigns should focus on the overrepresented segments for highest ROI.
